0.1 Flexible or Inflexible (3 points)

For each part, indicate whether we would generally expect the performance of a flexible statistical learning method to be better or worse than an inflexible method. Justify your answer.

  • The sample size \(n\) is extremely large, and the number of predictors \(p\) is small.
  • The number of predictors \(p\) is extremely large, and the number of observations \(n\) is small.
  • The relationship between the predictors and response is highly non-linear.
  • The variance of the error terms is extremely high.

Possible Solutions

  1. A flexible method is better. With only a few predictors, we can experiment with a wider set of models to obtain a better fit. A large sample will help reduce the bias.

  2. A flexible method is worse. It will involve too many parameters causing high variance and unstable estimates, especially for a small sample. A flexible method would overfit a small number of observations.

  3. A flexible method is better. Too many restrictions will allow only a few possible types of trends which may not capture the true nonlinear relationship. More degrees of freedom will yield a better fit.

  4. A flexible method is worse. A high error variance coupled with a high degree of flexibility will result in a high variance of estimates and unreliable conclusions.

0.3 Classification or Regression? (3 points)

Explain whether each scenario is a classification or regression problem, and indicate whether we are most interested in inference or prediction. Finally, provide \(n\) and \(p\).

  • We collect a set of data on the top 300 publicly-traded firms in the US. For each firm we record profit, number of employees, industry, average stock price over the last year, and the CEO salary. We are interested in understanding which factors affect CEO salary.

  • We are considering launching a new product and wish to know whether it will be a success or a failure. We collect data on 30 similar products that were previously launched. For each product we have recorded whether it was a success or failure, price charged for the product, marketing budget, competition price, and eight other variables.

  • We are interested in estimating future % changes in the US dollar in relation to the weekly changes in the world stock markets. Hence we collect weekly data for all of 2015. For each week we record the % change in the dollar, the % change in the British market, the % change in the Japanese market, and % change in the German market.

Possible Solutions

  1. Regression, \(n = 300\) companies, \(p = 4\) explanatory variables plus intercept. Inference as we are interested in what variables are important to the CEO salary.

  2. Classification, \(n = 30\) products, \(p = 11\) predictors. Prediction success or failure.

  3. Regression, \(n = 52\) weeks \(p = 3\) predictors plus intercept. Prediction as we are primarily interested in the quantitative value of response variable

0.4 Bias Variance Trade Off (3 points)

State True or False and then justify why the following are true or false in a single sentence.

  • Increasing degrees of freedom to be large enough will always reduce Mean Squared Error to 0.
  • Reducing bias is more important than reducing variance as a predicted value closer to the true value is always a better solution for your model.
  • Choosing 50% of the data for training data always provides the best balance between a good fit for the model and an accurate predicted MSE.

Possible Solutions

  1. False: MSE includes irreducible error that is usually non-zero.

  2. False: Reducing bias will make the average of predictions closer to the true value, but increased variance may mean any individual prediction is not close to the true value.

  3. False: The choice of how to split the data is part of tuning the model and 50% is not necessarily the best or even good for all situations.
